00:09:25.874 --> 00:09:27.290
PROFESSOR: Well,
the reason it has

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:30.060
to be plus or minus
1 for two particles,

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:31.420
so you said a couple of things.

00:09:31.420 --> 00:09:32.628
Let me answer the first part.

00:09:32.628 --> 00:09:34.920
So what I will call the first
part of your question is,

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:36.502
why did it have to
be plus or minus 1.

00:09:36.502 --> 00:09:38.390
Why couldn't it have
been an arbitrary phase?

00:09:38.390 --> 00:09:40.973
And the reason is that if you
do this exchange operation twice

00:09:40.973 --> 00:09:43.570
for two particles, you
get back the same thing.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:44.960
And that's what I mean by saying
I have identical particles.

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:46.060
Because I could
quibble with this.

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:46.810
You could say, well
look, you could

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:48.560
define some different
notion of exchange,

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:51.170
or under exchange, I
pick up an extra phase.

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:53.470
I swap them and then I swap
them and I swap them again,

00:09:53.470 --> 00:09:54.053
I get a phase.

00:09:54.053 --> 00:09:55.430
But here's the
problem with that.

00:09:55.430 --> 00:09:57.990
The problem with that is,
and this can be dealt with,

00:09:57.990 --> 00:10:01.329
but an interesting
question is if it can only

00:10:01.329 --> 00:10:02.870
be dealt with in
two dimensions or it

00:10:02.870 --> 00:10:04.953
can be dealt with in general
number of dimensions.

00:10:04.953 --> 00:10:08.030
This is a story called antions,
which Frank Wilczek here

00:10:08.030 --> 00:10:09.550
has really pounded hard on.

00:10:09.550 --> 00:10:10.800
But here's the basic question.

00:10:13.480 --> 00:10:16.910
So does the wave function
have a single value?

00:10:16.910 --> 00:10:18.054
I'd like to think it does.

00:10:18.054 --> 00:10:20.220
The wave function really
should have a single value.

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:21.490
If it has multiple
values, then it's

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:23.784
ambiguous what the value of
the wave function is there.

00:10:23.784 --> 00:10:24.450
That's not good.

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:26.530
That mean you have to specify
more than just the wave

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:28.580
function, you have to
specify which of the values

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:30.544
the wave function takes
in a particular point

00:10:30.544 --> 00:10:31.960
in the value of
the wave function.

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:35.270
So if under double
exchange we've

00:10:35.270 --> 00:10:37.000
returned to the
original configuration,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.080
you pick up a phase,
something is screwed.

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:43.384
You must be able to tell whether
or not you've exchanged twice,

00:10:43.384 --> 00:10:44.550
and here's why you can tell.

00:10:44.550 --> 00:10:46.850
Because while it's true that you
can't tell the overall phase,

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:49.140
imagine if I take my system
and I put in a splitter

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:52.662
and I have a beam
splitter I could think

00:10:52.662 --> 00:10:55.120
of it as a two-split experiment,
one component of that wave

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:58.289
function I will double swap and
the other component I will not.

00:10:58.289 --> 00:10:59.580
And then I will interfere them.

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:00.910
I will combine
them back together,

00:11:00.910 --> 00:11:02.160
do an interference experiment.

